\mt1 BARUCH. 
\c 1  
\m
\v 1  \sc And\sc* these \add are\add* the words of the book, which Baruch the son of Nerias, the son of Maasias, the son of Sedecias, the son of Asadias, the son of Chelcias, wrote in Babylon, 
\v 2 in the fifth year, \add and\add* in the seventh \add day\add* of the month, what time as the Chaldeans took Jerusalem, and burnt it with fire. 
\v 3 And Baruch did read the words of this book in the hearing of Jechonias the son of Joachim king of Juda, and in the ears of all the people that came to \add hear\add* the book, 
\v 4 and in the hearing of the nobles, and of the kings’ sons, and in the hearing of the elders, and of all the people, from the lowest unto the highest, \add even\add* of all them that dwelt at Babylon, by the river Sud. 
\v 5 Whereupon they wept, fasted, and prayed before the Lord. 
\v 6 They made also a collection of money according to every man’s power: 
\v 7 and they sent \add it\add* to Jerusalem unto Joachim the \add high\add* priest, the son of Chelcias, son of Salom, and to the priests, and to all the people which were found with him at Jerusalem, 
\v 8 at the same time when he received the vessels of the house of the Lord, that were carried out of the temple, to return \add them\add* into the land of Juda, the tenth \add day\add* of \add the month\add* Sivan, \add namely\add*, silver vessels, which Sedecias the son of Josias king of Juda \add had\add* made, 
\v 9 after that Nabuchodonosor king of Babylon had carried away Jechonias, and the princes, and the captives, and the mighty \add men\add*, and the people of the land, from Jerusalem, and brought them unto Babylon. 
\p
\v 10 And they said, Behold, we have sent you money to buy you burnt offerings, and sin offerings, and incense, and prepare ye manna, and offer upon the altar of the Lord our God; 
\v 11 and pray for the life of Nabuchodonosor king of Babylon, and for the life of Balthasar his son, that their days may be upon earth as the days of heaven: 
\v 12 and the Lord will give us strength, and lighten our eyes, and we shall live under the shadow of Nabuchodonosor king of Babylon, and under the shadow of Balthasar his son, and we shall serve them many days, and find favour in their sight. 
\v 13 Pray for us also unto the Lord our God, for we have sinned against the Lord our God; and unto this day the fury of the Lord and his wrath is not turned from us. 
\v 14 And ye shall read this book which we have sent unto you, to make confession in the house of the Lord, upon the feasts and solemn days. 
\v 15 And ye shall say, 
\p To the Lord our God \add belongeth\add* righteousness, but unto us the confusion of faces, as \add it is come to pass\add* this day, unto them of Juda, and to the inhabitants of Jerusalem, 
\v 16 and to our kings, and to our princes, and to our priests, and to our prophets, and to our fathers: 
\v 17 for we have sinned before the Lord, 
\v 18 and disobeyed him, and have not hearkened unto the voice of the Lord our God, to walk in the commandments that he gave us openly: 
\v 19 since the day that the Lord brought our forefathers out of the land of Egypt, unto this present day, we have been disobedient unto the Lord our God, and we have been negligent in not hearing his voice. 
\v 20 Wherefore the evils cleaved unto us, and the curse, which the Lord appointed by Moses his servant at the time that he brought our fathers out of the land of Egypt, to give us a land that floweth with milk and honey, \add like\add* as \add it is to see\add* this day. 
\v 21 Nevertheless we have not hearkened unto the voice of the Lord our God, according unto all the words of the prophets, whom he sent unto us: 
\v 22 but every man followed the imagination of his own wicked heart, to serve strange gods, \add and\add* to do evil in the sight of the Lord our God. 
\c 2  
\p
\v 1 Therefore the Lord hath made good his word, which he pronounced against us, and against our judges that judged Israel, and against our kings, and against our princes, and against the men of Israel and Juda, 
\v 2 to bring upon us great plagues, such as never happened under the whole heaven, as it came to pass in Jerusalem, according to the things that were written in the law of Moses; 
\v 3 that a man should eat the flesh of his own son, and the flesh of his own daughter. 
\v 4 Moreover he hath delivered them \add to be\add* in subjection to all the kingdoms that are round about us, to be \add as\add* a reproach and desolation among all the people round about, where the Lord hath scattered them. 
\v 5 Thus we were cast down, and not exalted, because we have sinned against the Lord our God, and have not been obedient unto his voice. 
\v 6 To the Lord our God \add appertaineth\add* righteousness: but unto us and to our fathers open shame, as \add appeareth\add* this day. 
\v 7  \add For\add* all these plagues are come upon us, which the Lord hath pronounced against us. 
\v 8 Yet have we not prayed before the Lord, that \add we\add* might turn every one from the imaginations of his wicked heart. 
\v 9 Wherefore the Lord watched \add over us\add* for evil, and the Lord hath brought \add it\add* upon us: for the Lord \add is\add* righteous in all his works which he hath commanded us. 
\v 10 Yet we have not hearkened unto his voice, to walk in the commandments of the Lord, that he hath set before us. 
\v 11 And now, O Lord God of Israel, that hast brought thy people out of the land of Egypt with a mighty hand, and high arm, and with signs, and with wonders, and with great power, and hast gotten thyself a name, as \add appeareth\add* this day: 
\v 12 O Lord our God, we have sinned, we have done ungodly, we have dealt unrighteously in all thine ordinances. 
\v 13 Let thy wrath turn from us: for we are \add but\add* a few left among the heathen, where thou hast scattered us. 
\v 14 Hear our prayers, O Lord, and our petitions, and deliver us for thine own sake, and give us favour in the sight of them which have led us away: 
\v 15 that all the earth may know that thou \add art\add* the Lord our God, because Israel and his posterity is called by thy name. 
\v 16 O Lord, look down from thy holy house, and consider us: bow down thine ear, O Lord, to hear \add us\add*. 
\v 17 Open thine eyes, and behold; for the dead \add that are\add* in the graves, whose souls are taken from their bodies, will give unto the Lord neither praise nor righteousness: 
\v 18 but the soul that is greatly vexed, which goeth stooping and feeble, and the eyes that fail, and the hungry soul, will give thee praise and righteousness, O Lord. 
\v 19 Therefore we do not make our humble supplication before thee, O Lord our God, for the righteousness of our fathers, and of our kings. 
\v 20 For thou hast sent out thy wrath and indignation upon us, as thou hast spoken by thy servants the prophets, saying, 
\p
\v 21 Thus saith the Lord, Bow down your shoulders to serve the king of Babylon: so shall ye remain in the land that I gave unto your fathers. 
\v 22 But if ye will not hear the voice of the Lord, to serve the king of Babylon, 
\v 23 I will cause to cease out of the cities of Juda, and from without Jerusalem, the voice of mirth, and the voice of joy, the voice of the bridegroom, and the voice of the bride: and the whole land shall be desolate of inhabitants. 
\p
\v 24 But we would not hearken unto thy voice, to serve the king of Babylon: therefore hast thou made good the words that thou spakest by thy servants the prophets, \add namely\add*, that the bones of our kings, and the bones of our fathers, should be taken out of their places. 
\v 25 And lo, they are cast out to the heat of the day, and to the frost of the night, and they died in great miseries by famine, by sword, and by pestilence. 
\v 26 And the house which is called by thy name hast thou laid \add waste\add*, as \add it is to be seen\add* this day, for the wickedness of the house of Israel and the house of Juda. 
\v 27 O Lord our God, thou hast dealt with us after all thy goodness, and according to all \add that\add* great mercy of thine, 
\v 28 as thou spakest by thy servant Moses in the day when thou didst command him to write thy law before the children of Israel, saying, 
\v 29 If ye will not hear my voice, surely this very great multitude shall be turned into a small \add number\add* among the nations, where I will scatter them. 
\v 30 For I knew that they would not hear me, because it is a stiffnecked people: but in the land of their captivities they shall remember themselves, 
\v 31 and shall know that I \add am\add* the Lord their God: for I will give them a heart, and ears to hear: 
\v 32 and they shall praise me in the land of their captivity, and think upon my name, 
\v 33 and return from their stiff neck, and from their wicked deeds: for they shall remember the way of their fathers, which sinned before the Lord. 
\v 34 And I will bring them again into the land which I promised with an oath unto their fathers, Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, and they shall be lords of it: and I will increase them, and they shall not be diminished. 
\v 35 And I will make an everlasting covenant with them to be their God, and they shall be my people: and I will no more drive my people of Israel out of the land that I have given them. 
\c 3  
\p
\v 1 O Lord Almighty, God of Israel, the soul in anguish, the troubled spirit, crieth unto thee. 
\v 2 Hear, O Lord, and have mercy; for thou art merciful: and have pity \add upon us\add*, because we have sinned before thee. 
\v 3 For thou endurest for ever, and we perish utterly. 
\v 4 O Lord Almighty, \add thou\add* God of Israel, hear now the prayers of the dead Israelites, and of \add their\add* children, which have sinned before thee, and not hearkened unto the voice of thee their God: for the which cause \add these\add* plagues cleave unto us. 
\v 5 Remember not the iniquities of our forefathers: but think upon thy power and thy name \add now\add* at this time. 
\v 6 For thou \add art\add* the Lord our God, and thee, O Lord, will we praise. 
\v 7 And for this cause thou hast put thy fear in our hearts, to the intent that \add we\add* should call upon thy name, and praise thee in our captivity: for we have called to mind all the iniquity of our forefathers, that sinned before thee. 
\v 8 Behold, we \add are yet\add* this day in our captivity, where thou hast scattered us, for a reproach and a curse, and to be subject to payments, according to all the iniquities of our fathers, which departed from the Lord our God. 
